um and jejunum only","Present in jejunum and ileum only","Present in duodenum only","Present in ileum only"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenum, jejunum and ileum\u003C/strong\u003E all contain goblet cells, which are specialised epithelial cells that secrete mucus. The density of goblet cells actually follows a gradient, with the highest concentration in the duodenum and decreasing numbers towards the ileum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe suggestion that goblet cells are \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent in duodenum and jejunum only\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent in jejunum and ileum only\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as they are found throughout the small intestine. Similarly, stating they are \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent in duodenum only\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Epresent in ileum only\u003C/strong\u003E fails to recognise their widespread distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGoblet cells serve important functions including:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecreting protective mucus that lubricates the intestinal surface\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreating a barrier between intestinal contents and epithelial cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContributing to innate immunity of the gastrointestinal tract\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Goblet cells are present throughout the entire small intestine but decrease in number from duodenum to ileum","Goblet cells secrete mucus that protects and lubricates the intestinal epithelium"],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada